    a: "Most candidates will either have deep AVEVA product knowledge or deep shipbuilding project experience — rarely both. I bring 15 years of naval engineering programs where PLM discipline wasn't optional — it was the difference between acceptance and rejection. I know what it feels like when engineering data isn't controlled, and I know how to fix it. I also have direct customer-facing experience: presenting at FAT, managing field escalations, closing issues with evidence. That combination — structured engineering discipline, customer-facing communication, and fast learning — is what makes a Principal Engineer actually useful to Korean shipyards.",
